<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-002-260 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 600 550</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 9 1991 v8 n49 p126(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM, Apple near naming of boards for joint ventures. (Taligent andKalieda) (Brief Article)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Freedman, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Joint ventures)Apple Computer Inc. (Joint ventures)Taligent (Management)Kaleida (Management).andO;Ticker:    IBM; AAPL.andO;Topic:     Computer industryJoint VentureBoard of Directors.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Beth FreedmanandM;Though still actively conducting a CEO search, IBM and Apple Computer Inc.andO;are in the process of formalizing the boards of directors for their two jointventures, sources said.andM;The newfound partners are planning to introduce in January the boards andmanagement of Kaleida and Taligent -- multimedia and operating-systemcompanies, respectively -- assuming they get the Justice Department'sapproval, said sources familiar with the firms' plans.andM;Taligent, which is working on an object-oriented operating system based onApple's existing Pink project, will likely be served by a six-member board.andO;Among the members will be IBM Vice President Joseph Guglielmi, also generalmanager of marketing and business development for personal systems, and DavidNagel, vice president of Apple's Advanced Technology Group.andM;Another pair of IBM and Apple executives will sit on the board, along withtwo representatives from the financial community, sources said.andP;  EdwardBirss, a senior vice president at Apple, will be chief operating officer forTaligent, which will be based in Santa Clara, Calif.andM;&quot;Naming a board of directors is the first order of business,&quot; said PaulBergevin, an IBM spokesman in Armonk, N.Y.andP;  &quot;Certain individuals in bothcompanies have been asked if they'd like to serve on the board.&quot; Bergevindeclined to comment on specifics.andM;IBM Vice President James Cannavino, Apple Chairman John Sculley and IBM VicePresident of New Systems Development David Liddle --the long-rumored topcandidate for the Taligent CEO post -- will not serve on either board,sources said.andM;Expected to participate on Kaleida's board will be Apple's Nagel and RobertCarberry, IBM's assistant general manager of the Entry Systems Division.andO;Carberry is also in the running to head Kaleida, whose location is stillundecided, sources said.andM;Even without a set management team, Taligent has already undergone someturnover.andP;  Ronald Lang, a former Apple employee who was to serve as a keymarketing executive, recently left to join NeXT Inc., sources said.andP;  Langcould not be reached for comment.andO;</TEXT></DOC>